Summary

Overview of this document

This HTML page provides information about Aim 1, including

  • Study objectives
  • Definitions and descriptive statistics for the (a) outcome variables and (b) independent variables/covariates
  • Example maps made using R studio to demonstrate the distribution of cannabis outlets in a few legalized states
  • Unadjusted and adjusted multilevel model results examining the relationship between the 4 outcomes and each covariate.

Aim 1: Study Objectives

  1. Compare community characteristics among census tracts with and without RCDs in states that have legalized retail sales of recreational cannabis.

  2. Describe the association between RCD locations and community characteristics on the census tract level.

    • Use unadjusted & adjusted multilevel models to identify statistically significant correlates of RCD counts and measures of RCD density.

  3. Use spatial statistics (e.g., Morans I) to identify the extent census tracts are more closely correlated with their neighbor tracts.

Data Sample

  • 18 states that have legalized marijuana for recreational, adult use (Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Connecticut, Illinois, Maine, Massachusetts, Michigan, Missouri, Montana, Nevada, New Jersey, New Mexico, New York, Oregon, Rhode Island , Vermont, Washington)
  • Total of n=30,225 census tracts with greater than a 0 population

Data Overview

The two tabs below describe the outcome variables and the independent variables for analysis.

Outcome variables

Outcome variables include:

  • Whether or not a census tract has a dispensary (1=at least one) or not (0) (can_bin)
  • Count: the number of RCDs in a census tract (cannabis_count)
  • Density per population: the number of RCDs per 1000 population (cdensitypop)
  • Density per land area: the number of RCDs per square mile (cdensityland)
  • Density per roadway: the number of RCDS per 10 km of roadway (cdensityroad)

Independent Variables

Below you will find definitions and summary statistics for all the independent variables / census tract characteristics considered for this analysis organized by broad category. All sociodemographic data was obtained from the the American Community Survey 2017-2021 5-year estimates.

Sociodemographics

  • Age: percent of census tract population under 18 years of age (percent_under18)
  • Gender: percent of census tract population that is female (percent_female)
  • Non-Hispanic (NH) White: percent of NH census tract population that identify as white (percent_white)
  • Non-Hispanic (NH) Black: percent of NH census tract population that identify as Black (percent_black)
  • Hispanic: percent of census tract population that identify as Hispanic (percent_hispanic)
  • Proportion non-white: percent of census tract population that identifies as a race or ethnicity other than NH, white (percent_nonwhite)

Measures of Deprivation or Privilege

Income and Poverty

  • Median household income (med_hh_income) (scaled per $1000)
  • Percent of households living under the federal poverty line (FPL) (pctpov)
  • Proportion of the labor force that is currently unemployed (among population 16+)

Education

  • Percent with less than a high school degree (among population 25+) (percent_lesshs)
  • Percent with a bachelor’s college degree or more (among population 25+) (percent_bachelor)

Household characteristics

  • Proportion of single parent households (percent_singlefamhouse)
  • Proportion of households that speak/prefer a language other than English at home (percent_noteng)
  • Percent of families receiving public assistance income in the past 12 months (percent_assist)

Housing

  • Median home value (median_home_value) (scaled per $1000)
  • Proportion of housing units that are renter-occupied (percent_renter)
  • Proportion of housing units that are vacant (percent_vacant)
  • Percent of housing units that have been rented/owned for 5 years or less

Measures of Segregation

Location Quotient: a measure of concentration/clustering and presents the relative homogeneity of each census tract as compared to the overall MSA

  • LQ_NH_White_Alone: the percent of non-Hispanic, white residents in the CT as compared to the percent of white residents within the overall MSA. A value of 1 indicate that the census tract has the same share of white residents as compared to the larger MSA. A LQ greater than 1 indicates a greater concentration of white residents compared to the larger MSA.
  • LQ_Black_Alone: the percent of non-Hispanic, Black residents in the CT as compared to the percent of Black residents within the overall MSA. A value of 1 indicate that the census tract has the same share of Black residents as compared to the larger MSA. A LQ greater than 1 indicates a greater concentration of Blacks residents relative to the larger MSA.
  • LQ_Hispanic: the percent of white residents in the CT as compared to the percent of white residents within the overall MSA. A value of 1 indicate that the census tract has the same share of white residents as compared to the larger MSA. A LQ greater than 1 indicates a greater concentration of white residents compared to the larger MSA.

Index of Concentration at the Extremes (ICE): a measure that quantifies levels of racial privilege versus racial deprivation. ICE is a continuous variable that ranges from \(???1\) to 1, where \(???1\) corresponds with complete deprivation and 1 with completed privilege.

  • ICE_Black_Alone_White_Alone: The ICE race privilege group is non-Hispanic White people and the deprived group non-Hispanic Black people.
  • ICE_Hispanic_NH_White_Alone: The ICE race privilege group is non-Hispanic White people and the deprived group Hispanic.

Local Exposure and Isolation Index (LEx/Is): Measures the probability that two individuals living within a census tract of either different or the same racial/ethnic group(s) will interact. A value of 0 means that the chance of two people from different racial/ethnic groups interacting in a given census tract is equal to the expected probability if the MSA were perfectly mixed. Values greater than zero indicate that the interaction is more likely to occur within the census tract than in the MSA, and values less than zero indicate that it is less likely.

  • Lex_Is_Black_Alone_White_Alone: LEX/Is for Black/White Interaction in the census tract
  • Lex_Is_Hispanic_NH_White_Alone: LEX/Is for Hispanic/White Interaction in the census tract

Environmental Characteristics

  • Walkability score (AVGWALK): The National Walkability Index ranks census tracts according to their relative walkability. A greater value indicates greater walkability.

Schools

  • School count: the total number of schools in a census tract (school_count)
  • School binary variable: Whether a census tract has a school or not (school_bin)

Parks

  • Park count: the total number of parks in a census tract (park_count)
  • Proportion of census tract area that is park space (percent_parkarea)
  • Park binary variable: Whether a census tract has a park or not (park_bin)

Retailers

  • Business count: the total number of retail businesses in a census tract (business_count)
  • Average retail sales amount ($) of retail business per census tract (mean_sales) (scaled per $ 100)
  • Total number of retail sales amount ($) of retail businesses per census tract (sum_sales) (scaled per $1000)

Unadjusted and Adjusted Results

  • Unadjusted models: Univariate relationship between the covariate and the outcome

  • Adjusted model #1: Covariates include population density, land area, urban/rural classification, U.S. Region

  • Adjusted model #2: Covariates include % female, % under 18, % white, % black, % Hispanic, % below FPL, education (less HS, bachelors degree), unemployment, % receiving public assistance, % renters, % vacant units, Lex/Is BW, Lex/Is HW, walkability score, percent park area, # of schools

Key Highlights

  • RCD density differs by census tract characteristics, in other words, density is not distributed across all community characteristics in the same way.
  • The extent and direction of these associations differ depending on the measure used

There are n=3341 census tracts with dispensaries and n=26884 census tracts with no dispensaries.

  • 11% of the census tracts have at least 1 RCD.

Compared to census tracts with 0 dispensaries, Census tracts with dispensaries are more likely to have:

  • more NH, white residents (61% vs 56%)
  • lower median household income (68K vs 83K)
  • greater proportion of residents living under the federal poverty line (FPL) (15% vs 12%)
  • lower percentage of residents who prefer a language other than English (24% vs 29%)
  • greater proportion of renter-occupied units (39% vs 33%)
  • greater count of parks (3.18 vs 2.48)
  • greater retail activity (number of businesses, average sales/$1000, and total sales/1000 dollars )
